steps.description:
The cyanotype is made up of two simple solutions. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/50/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
Potassium ferricyanide and
Ferric ammonium citrate (green) are mixed with water separately. The two solutions are then blended together in equal parts. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Dissolve the chemicals in water to make two separate solutions. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add Ammonium ferric citrate to water into one container and Potassium ferricyanide to water in another. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8c/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8c/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Stir with a plastic spoon until the chemicals dissolve. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1c/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Mix equal quantities of each solution together in a third container. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Unused solutions can be stored separately in brown bottles away from light, but will not last very long once they have been mixed. Dispose of any unused chemicals in a sensible and environmentally friendly way! {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet7.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet7.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using a brush, simply paint the chemicals onto the material. Paper, card, textiles or any natural material can be used to print on. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Decide how big your print is going to be, and cut your material to size. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/53/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/53/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure your working area is dimly lit, or lit with a low-level tungsten bulb. Once the material is coated, leave it to dry in the dark. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Print a cyanotype by placing your negative (to reproduce a photograph) or object (to make a photogram) in contact with your coated paper or fabric. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sandwich it with a piece of glass. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/06/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/06/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Expose the sandwich to UV light. Natural sunlight is the traditional light source, but UV lamps can also be used. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Print-Photographs-in-the-Sun-Using-the-Classic-Cyanotype-Process-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
A photogram can also be made by placing items on the surface. Plants, decorative items or other objects can be used to create silhouettes or interesting shapes. Exposure times can vary from a few minutes to several hours, depending on how strong your light source is or the season where you are printing.

